{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_8","type":"command_execution","command":"/run/current-system/sw/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/prompt.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Implement `ralph-burning` v1 Rewrite\n\n## 1) Objective and Source of Truth\nYou are implementing a greenfield Rust rewrite of the orchestrator in `ralph-burning-rewrite/`. The existing code in `multibackend-orchestration/` is **read-only reference-only** for behavior inference; do not preserve or migrate legacy `.ralph` state, artifact formats, loop directories, or git checkpoint encoding.\n\n## 2) Product Definition\nBuild a modular monolith called `ralph-burning` with one binary and these hard constraints:\n- Rust implementation.\n- New workspace root is `.ralph-burning/`.\n- Built-in flow presets are exactly: `standard`, `quick_dev`, `docs_change`, `ci_improvement`.\n- No arbitrary user-defined flow DSL in v1.\n- Markdown is only a rendered, human-readable artifact, not workflow protocol.\n- Canonical workflow state is structured stage payload JSON + run state + journal.\n- Runtime logs are ephemeral and never part of durable project history.\n\n## 3) Non-goals\n- No compatibility layer for old `.ralph` workspaces or legacy reconstruction logic.\n- No service-oriented microservice split in v1.\n- No full implementation of every slice before completing core canonical state and shared engine.\n\n## 4) Canonical Vocabulary (must use consistently)\n- `workspace`: orchestration root `.ralph-burning/`\n- `project`: durable work item with immutable `flow`\n- `run`: execution instance for a project\n- `stage`: named step in a flow preset\n- `stage cursor`: current stage + cycle + attempt metadata\n- `work cycle`: unit of iterative delivery work\n- `completion round`: unit deciding complete vs continue\n- `backend family`: e.g., Claude, Codex, OpenRouter\n- `stage contract`: schema + required fields + semantic validation rules\n- `stage payload`: validated structured output\n- `history artifact`: rendered Markdown derived from payload\n- `runtime log`: operational/debug output\n- `journal`: append-only domain event log\n- `rollback point`: durable logical checkpoint\n- `task`: daemon unit of automated work\n\nDecision in this prompt:\n- Use canonical term `cycle` in public docs and CLI; accept `loop` as deprecated alias only for informational output, not as a primary API term.\n\n## 5) Bounded Contexts (required)\nImplement the following context packages with ports/adapters boundaries:\n\n- `contexts/workspace_governance/*`\n- `contexts/project_run_record/*`\n- `contexts/workflow_composition/*`\n- `contexts/agent_execution/*`\n- `contexts/requirements_drafting/*`\n- `contexts/automation_runtime/*`\n- `contexts/conformance_spec/*`\n- `adapters/*` for side effects\n\nPrimary dependencies:\n- `workspace_governance` is upstream for config and flow discovery.\n- `project_run_record` is source of durable truth.\n- `workflow_composition` drives run progression.\n- `agent_execution` provides invocation + normalized structured results.\n- `automation_runtime` consumes routing and dispatches into workflow/requirements.\n\n## 6) Folder and Storage Layout\nUse this model in `ralph-burning-rewrite/`:\n\n`src/`\n- `main.rs`\n- composition, shared, contexts, adapters, etc. as per provided package sketch.\n\n`.ralph-burning/`\n- `workspace.toml`\n- `active-project`\n- `projects/<project-id>/project.toml`\n- `projects/<project-id>/prompt.md`\n- `projects/<project-id>/run.json`\n- `projects/<project-id>/journal.ndjson`\n- `projects/<project-id>/sessions.json`\n- `projects/<project-id>/history/payloads/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/history/artifacts/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/runtime/logs/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/runtime/backend/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/runtime/temp/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/amendments/*`\n- `projects/<project-id>/rollback/*`\n- `requirements/<requirements-run-id>/*`\n- `daemon/tasks/*`\n- `daemon/leases/*`\n\nYou must persist:\n- canonical project metadata and active run state\n- payload records and payload-derived artifacts\n- journal and runtime-log metadata/indexes\n- rollback points and amendment queue\n\n## 7) Core Invariants (MUST pass)\n- Each project has one immutable flow preset.\n- Every active run has one stage cursor.\n- Stage cursor stage must belong to the project’s selected flow.\n- Cycle and completion round numbers are monotonic and independent.\n- Structured payload validation must happen before any state mutation.\n- Domain validation must happen after schema validation, before transition commit.\n- Durable project history = journal + payloads + rendered artifacts only.\n- Runtime logs are never promoted into durable history.\n- Starting `run start` on a project with an active run must resume or fail with explicit message; it must not create duplicate active runs.\n- Resume is allowed only from durable stage boundaries.\n- Terminal state transitions persist before cleanup of external side effects when possible.\n- Explicit model overrides trump role defaults.\n- Session reuse only for roles/backends that explicitly allow it.\n- Cancellation and timeout must immediately halt retries for the run/call.\n- One writer lock per project.\n- One active daemon task per issue.\n- One worktree lease per task.\n- Command-based routing overrides label-based routing; label overrides repo default.\n- Hard rollback: logical rollback must happen before repository reset.\n- Unsupported workspace versions fail fast with no implicit migration.\n\n## 8) CLI Contract (v1 surface)\nAll commands exit non-zero on invalid state or policy failures.\n\nWorkspace/config:\n- `ralph-burning init`\n- `ralph-burning config show`\n- `ralph-burning config get <key>`\n- `ralph-burning config set <key> <value>`\n- `ralph-burning config edit`\n\nFlow discovery:\n- `ralph-burning flow list`\n- `ralph-burning flow show <flow-id>`\n\nProjects:\n- `ralph-burning project create --id <id> --name <name> --prompt <file> --flow <flow-id>`\n- `ralph-burning project select <id>`\n- `ralph-burning project list`\n- `ralph-burning project show [<id>]`\n- `ralph-burning project delete <id>`\n\nRun lifecycle:\n- `ralph-burning run start`\n- `ralph-burning run resume`\n- `ralph-burning run status`\n- `ralph-burning run history`\n- `ralph-burning run tail [--logs]`\n- `ralph-burning run rollback --to <target> [--hard]`\n\nRequirements:\n- `ralph-burning requirements draft --idea \"<text>\"`\n- `ralph-burning requirements quick --idea \"<text>\"`\n- `ralph-burning requirements show <run-id>`\n- `ralph-burning requirements answer <run-id>`\n\nDaemon:\n- `ralph-burning daemon start`\n- `ralph-burning daemon status`\n- `ralph-burning daemon abort <task-id>`\n- `ralph-burning daemon retry <task-id>`\n- `ralph-burning daemon reconcile`\n\nConformance:\n- `ralph-burning conformance list`\n- `ralph-burning conformance run [--filter <scenario-id>]`\n\nClarifications for CLI behavior:\n- `run tail` shows durable history only by default.\n- `run tail --logs` appends latest runtime logs.\n- `loop` is accepted only as a user-facing alias; `cycle` is canonical in docs and output schema.\n\n## 9) Built-in Flow Presets (v1)\nFlows are fixed per project at creation and cannot change.\nFlow stages are deterministic and configured in code:\n- `standard`: `prompt_review` (optional by config) → `planning` → `implementation` → `qa` → `review` → `completion_panel` → `acceptance_qa` → `final_review` (preset-driven)\n- `quick_dev`: `plan_and_implement` → `review` → `apply_fixes` → `final_review`\n- `docs_change`: `docs_plan` → `docs_update` → `docs_validation` → `review`\n- `ci_improvement`: `ci_plan` → `ci_update` → `ci_validation` → `review`\n\nValidation profile and final review defaults:\n- `standard`: final review enabled.\n- `quick_dev`: final review enabled, lightweight panel.\n- `docs_change`: final review disabled by default.\n- `ci_improvement`: final review disabled by default.\n\nValidation profiles include all required checks named in each preset’s default profile and may add policy-specific stricter checks when explicitly configured.\n\n## 10) Structured Stage Contracts (mandatory)\nFor every supported stage:\n- Define `StageContract` with JSON schema.\n- Persist raw backend output for diagnostics.\n- Validate payload schema first.\n- Apply semantic domain validation second.\n- Render Markdown deterministically from payload after successful validation.\n- Do not parse Markdown for state transitions.\n- Persist both payload and rendered artifact atomically under project history.\n\nRetry and failure classes must be explicit:\n- transport failure\n- schema validation failure\n- domain-validation failure\n- timeout\n- cancellation\n- qa/review outcome failure\nDifferent classes must map to distinct retry/terminal policies.\n\n## 11) Project and Run Record Rules\n`project` model stores:\n- id, name, prompt reference/hash, fixed flow, active run pointer, run state, stage cursor, cycle history, completion rounds, sessions, amendment queue, rollback points, status summary, and journal pointer.\n\nRun state transitions must never infer from artifacts.  \n`journal.ndjson` is the authoritative event source.\nState reads (`status`, `history`, `tail`) derive from canonical run/journal, not artifact scans.\n\n## 12) Agent Execution\nEvery backend invocation must produce structured stage payload-compatible output.\nEngine responsibilities:\n- parse backend spec and model spec\n- resolve per-role backend/model\n- verify backend capability for target stage contract before run start\n- check availability\n- invoke with timeout and cancellation\n- normalize to standard invocation envelope\n- preserve raw output in runtime logs\nUnsupported or mis-structured backend outputs must fail the stage with explicit class and no state transition.\n\n## 13) Automation Routing\nImplement daemon task routing with these precedence rules:\n1. explicit routing command (e.g., `/rb flow <flow-id>`)\n2. routing label (e.g., `rb:flow:<flow-id>`)\n3. repository default\n\nLabel vocabulary baseline:\n- `rb:flow:standard`\n- `rb:flow:quick_dev`\n- `rb:flow:docs_change`\n- `rb:flow:ci_improvement`\n- command and label values are validated against built-in presets only.\n\n## 14) Delivery Roadmap (Minimum v1 order)\nExecute in bounded slices with explicit handoff gates:\n\n1) Charter + v1 domain model + scenario IDs + workspace init + flow discovery.  \n2) Flow preset definitions + stage contracts + renderer contracts.  \n3) Workspace governance effective config + active project resolution.  \n4) Project/run canonical store + journal + query commands.  \n5) Agent execution facade with structured-output guarantee.  \n6) Standard preset vertical path (`run start`) end-to-end with schema/renderer persistence.  \n7) Retry/remediation, prompt review, resume, and failure class semantics.  \n8) Completion/acceptance/final-review behavior + amendment queue.  \n9) docs and CI preset integration on same engine.  \n10) Requirements drafting and project-seed handoff.  \n11) Daemon routing, tasks, leases, watchers, rebase, interactive requirements path.  \n12) Cutover: no legacy runtime paths in v1 entrypoint; conformance gate in CI.\n\n## 15) Testability Requirements (hard constraints)\n- All public behavior is defined in Gherkin under `tests/conformance/features/`.\n- Every flow preset and routing policy has scenario coverage.\n- Conformance must include scenario filtering and fail-fast semantics (non-zero exit if any selected scenario fails).\n- For each context, implement:\n  - pure domain/unit tests for state and transition rules\n  - service-level tests with fake ports\n  - adapter contract tests\n  - targeted integration tests\n- Core invariants must have property/invariant tests where feasible.\n- Regression protection: any change to public flow behavior must update/extend corresponding scenario IDs.","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_9","type":"command_execution","command":"/run/current-system/sw/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' /root/new-ralph-burning/.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/loops/004-project-and-run-record-foundation/20260311194558-spec.md\"","aggregated_output":"---\nartifact: spec\nloop: 4\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\nrole: planner\ncreated_at: 2026-03-11T19:45:58Z\n---\n\nI’m reviewing `prompt.md`, the completed loop specs, and recent git checkpoints to determine what is already covered and what the next unimplemented slice should be. First I’ll map the current planning artifacts against the roadmap and the codebase state so I don’t re-spec completed work.\nI’ve confirmed the branch is sitting just after Loop 3 planning, with loops 1 through 3 committed in git and conformance coverage matching those slices. Next I’m reading the actual spec artifacts and the current Rust modules to check whether roadmap step 4 has already been partially built or only stubbed.\nThe loop artifacts live under the hidden `.ralph/` planning workspace, not in the Rust crate itself. I’m reading those specs plus the current source modules now to determine whether the next slice is the canonical project/run store from roadmap step 4 or whether some of that was already pulled forward.\nThe approved specs line up cleanly with roadmap slices 1 through 3. I’m now checking the current `project_run_record`, `project` CLI, and `run` CLI surfaces to see whether any slice-4 behavior already exists, so the next spec only covers the actual gap.\nSlice 4 is still empty in code: `project_run_record` is only a stub, `project create/list/show/delete` are unimplemented, and every `run` subcommand still exits `NotYetImplemented`. I’m confirming there isn’t hidden project/run persistence elsewhere and then I’ll draft the next feature around that gap.\nI’ve verified there’s no hidden implementation beyond Loop 3. To tighten the next spec, I’m pulling the architecture notes for the `project_run_record` context from the repo docs so the acceptance criteria line up with the intended storage model and invariants, not just the roadmap headline.\nThe roadmap and architecture notes both point to the same next gap: `Project & Run Record`. I’m pulling the scenario notes around project creation and durable-history-vs-runtime-log separation so the spec includes the right invariants for failure handling and query behavior.\nI have enough to choose the slice. I’m doing one last pass over the shared error types and current storage helpers so the file list and failure-mode criteria match the crate’s existing structure instead of inventing a parallel design.\n# Feature: Project and Run Record Foundation\n\n## Description\nLoops 1 through 3 are complete: the rewrite already has workspace bootstrap, built-in flow discovery, stage-contract/rendering infrastructure, and workspace governance with effective config plus active-project resolution. The next missing slice is roadmap step 4: make `project_run_record` the durable source of truth by implementing canonical project storage, initial run/journal state, project CRUD, and read-only run query commands.\n\nCurrent HEAD still has `src/contexts/project_run_record/mod.rs` as a stub, `project create/list/show/delete` unimplemented, and all `run` commands unimplemented. This feature should fill that gap without re-planning completed flow, config, or active-project work.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `ralph-burning project create --id <id> --name <name> --prompt <file> --flow <flow-id>` validates workspace version, project ID, flow preset, prompt readability, and duplicate IDs before any filesystem mutation.\n- [ ] Successful project creation writes `.ralph-burning/projects/<project-id>/project.toml`, `prompt.md`, `run.json`, `journal.ndjson`, `sessions.json`, `history/payloads/`, `history/artifacts/`, `runtime/logs/`, `runtime/backend/`, `runtime/temp/`, `amendments/`, and `rollback/`.\n- [ ] `project.toml` persists immutable project metadata: `id`, `name`, fixed `flow`, copied prompt reference, prompt hash, creation timestamp, and durable status summary. Flow cannot be changed after creation by any CLI or store path.\n- [ ] `run.json` persists canonical run state only: active run pointer, run status, optional stage cursor, cycle history, completion rounds, rollback-point metadata, amendment-queue state, and status summary. It must not infer state from artifacts or logs.\n- [ ] `journal.ndjson` is append-only, sequence-ordered, and initialized with a `project_created` event. Queries derive state from canonical run state plus journal, never from Markdown scans.\n- [ ] `sessions.json` initializes as a valid empty session store, separate from durable history.\n- [ ] `project create` is atomic. If prompt copy, snapshot write, or journal initialization fails, the new project is not visible to `project list/show`, no partial canonical files remain exposed, and `.ralph-burning/active-project` is unchanged.\n- [ ] Duplicate project creation fails non-zero with a clear error and leaves existing project state unchanged.\n- [ ] `project create` does not implicitly select the new project; active-project mutation remains the job of the already-implemented `project select`.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning project list` reads canonical project records, not raw directory names, and shows enough summary data to identify each project plus whether it is the active selection.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning project show [<id>]` shows explicit project data when `<id>` is provided and otherwise resolves the active project through workspace governance. Output includes flow, prompt hash/reference, created timestamp, run summary, and rollback summary.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning project delete <id>` deletes only projects with no active run. If the deleted project was selected, `.ralph-burning/active-project` is cleared only after the delete succeeds. If delete fails after validation, the project remains addressable and the active-project pointer is unchanged.\n- [ ] Add payload/artifact store models and enumeration APIs for durable history. If a payload write succeeds but its artifact companion write/index fails, `run history` and `run tail` must not expose a partial durable-history record.\n- [ ] Runtime logs are stored and queried separately from durable history. Runtime-log write failures must not fabricate, remove, or reorder durable history.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning run status` reads canonical state for the active project and reports either “not started” or the persisted run snapshot without inferring from artifacts.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning run history` shows durable history only: journal events plus payload/artifact records in canonical order. Runtime logs never appear there.\n- [ ] `ralph-burning run tail` shows durable history only by default, and `ralph-burning run tail --logs` appends the newest runtime logs after the durable section without changing the durable-history portion.\n- [ ] Corrupt or inconsistent canonical files (`project.toml`, `run.json`, `journal.ndjson`, payload/artifact indexes) fail fast with file-specific errors. Commands must not fall back to rendered Markdown or directory scans when canonical state is invalid.\n- [ ] Introduce `ProjectStorePort`, `JournalStorePort`, `ArtifactStorePort`, and `RuntimeLogStorePort` boundaries inside `contexts/project_run_record`, with filesystem-backed adapters using atomic writes/renames.\n- [ ] Add domain/unit tests for immutable flow, journal sequencing, and history/log separation; service tests with fake ports; adapter contract tests for filesystem round trips and corruption visibility; and CLI integration tests for project CRUD plus run queries.\n- [ ] Add public Gherkin coverage for project creation, duplicate IDs, immutable flow, list/show/delete behavior, no-active-run status, durable-history-only queries, and `run tail --logs` separation semantics.\n- [ ] `cargo test` and `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` pass.\n\n## Files to Modify/Create\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/mod.rs` - expose the context surface, core ports, and public use cases\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/model.rs` - define project records, run snapshots, journal events, payload/artifact records, runtime-log records, and rollback metadata\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/service.rs` - implement create/list/show/delete and run query use cases with invariant checks\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/queries.rs` - build canonical read models for status, history, and tail\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/project_run_record/journal.rs` - define append/read ordering and sequence validation for `journal.ndjson`\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/adapters/fs.rs` - add atomic project staging, canonical snapshot reads/writes, NDJSON append helpers, prompt hashing, and active-project clearing on delete\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/cli/project.rs` - replace stubs for `create`, `list`, `show`, and `delete` while preserving existing `select`\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/cli/run.rs` - implement `status`, `history`, and `tail`; keep `start`, `resume`, and `rollback` as later-slice work\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/src/shared/error.rs` - add duplicate-project, corrupt-record, invalid-prompt, active-run-delete, and journal-sequence error variants\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/project_records.feature` - public scenarios for project CRUD and immutable flow\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_queries.feature` - public scenarios for status/history/tail and runtime-log separation\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/project_run_record_test.rs` - domain and service tests for project/run invariants\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/journal_test.rs` - journal ordering, corruption, and append semantics\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/query_test.rs` - durable-history and runtime-log separation tests\n- `ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/cli.rs` - CLI integration coverage for project and run query commands\n\n## Dependencies\n- Requires: Loop 1 foundation, Loop 2 stage contract registry and deterministic rendering, Loop 3 workspace governance effective config and active project resolution\n- Blocks: Agent-driven `run start` orchestration, resume/retry/rollback semantics, and requirements-to-project handoff\n\n---\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
